            "9": [
                {   "id": "COM109E112",
                    "name": "Computing Essentials 9 Standard",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "S",
                    "description": "“Computing Essentials” is a compulsory selective course for 9th grade. This course is offered to students who want to improve their understanding of necessary concepts and skills of computer science. This course also endeavors to instill an appreciation for the effect of information technology on people and our environment and to give you a basis for building the necessary skill set to succeed in the 21st century. In brief, this course introduces students to the technical and application concepts of computer science in multiple areas, such as Python programming basic, digital processing, web designing, a basic understanding of application packages in word processing and spreadsheet software, the architecture of the computer, network basic, and troubleshooting skills for computers. After this course, students will have a better experience in computer science and be more able to apply it to the working world. Besides, this course provides a solid foundation for students’ continued studies in computer sciences.",
                    "rules": {
                        "next": [["COM110E110", "COM110E130"]]
                    }
                }, { "id": "COM109E130",
                    "name": "Programming Methodology 9 Honors",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "H",
                    "description": "“Programming Methodology” is a compulsory selective course for grade 9 students and will benefit those who want to study IB/AP computer science in future. It is also a prerequisite for Honors Computer fundamentals 10. The content of this course mainly embraces the basic knowledge of programming, the introduction of commonly used controls and some programming related concepts. A large part of the course is built around the development of computer programs that correctly solve a given problem. After finishing this course, every student should acquire the ability to analyze and solve simple real-life problems by the programming tools they have learned. Homework Expectation: 3-4 hours per week",
                    "rules": {
                        "next": [["COM110E130", "COM110E170"]]
                    }
                }
            ], "10": [
                {   "id": "COM110E110",
                    "name": "Computer Fundamentals 10 Standard",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "S",
                    "description": "“Standard Computer Fundamentals” is a compulsory selective course for 10th grade students. It helps students to expand their knowledge of computers in Information Age. The requirements of this course are comparatively lower than course “Honors Computer Fundamentals”. The contents in this course cover a wide variety of topics in computer science fields, including hardware, software, multimedia, network, database, programming, ethics and careers in IT. A large part of the course is built around lectures, discussion, classroom assignments, lab experiments and homework. After finishing this course, all students should understand the commonly used CS terminology in their daily life and develop the ability to think critically and communicate effectively. Homework Expectation: 2-3 hours per week",
                    "rules": { "next": [["COM110E130", "COM111E100"]] }
                }, { "id": "COM110E130",
                    "name": "Computer Fundamentals 10 Honors",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "H",
                    "description": "“Honors Computer Fundamentals” is a compulsory selective course for 10th grade. Compared to course “Standard Computer Fundamentals”, this course offers the cultivation of computational thinking in addition. In other words, this course is separated into two parts: computer concepts and problem solving with programming. First of all, computer concepts, computer literacy such as software, hardware, network, and database, etc, will be mentioned in class. Students will have the chance to learn how a computer works step by step in detail. Besides, using problem solving with programming skills such as operations, algorithms, and data structure will be included in this course. Students will be able to make small products at the end of this course. In addition, a project with written reports which can be treated as seminar talks is also a part of this course. Homework Expectation: 3-4 hours per week",
                    "rules": {
                        "pre": [["COM109E130"]],
                        "next": [["COM111E170", "COM111E140", "COM111E150"]]
                    }
                }, { "id": "COM110E170",
                    "name": "AP Computer Science Principles 10",
                    "track": "AP",
                    "description": "AP Computer Science Principles introduces students to the breadth of the field of computer science. In this course, students will learn to design and evaluate solutions and to apply computer science to solve problems through the development of algorithms and programs. They will incorporate abstraction into programs and use data to discover new knowledge. Students will also explain how computing innovations and computing systems, including the Internet, work, explore their potential impacts, and contribute to a computing culture that is collaborative and ethical. This course focuses on big ideas that encompass core principles, theories, and processes of the discipline: \n• creative development\n• data\n• algorithms and programming\n• computing systems and networks\n• impact of computing\nHomework Expectation: 4-5 hours per week",
                    "rules": {
                        "pre": [["COM109E130"]],
                        "next": [["COM111E170"]]
                    }
                }
            ], "11": [
                {   "id": "COM111E170",
                    "name": "AP Computer Science A 11",
                    "track": "AP",
                    "description": "AP Computer Science A introduces students to computer science through programming. Fundamental topics in this course include the design of solutions to problems, the use of data structures to organize large sets of data, the development and implementation of algorithms to process data and discover new information, the analysis of potential solutions, and the ethical and social implications of computing systems. The course emphasizes object-oriented programming and design using the Java programming language. The contents of this course come as follows:\n• Using Objects and Methods\n• Selection and Iteration\n• Class Creation\n• Data Collections\nHomework Expectation: 4-5 hours per week",
                    "rules": {
                        "pre": [["COM110E170", "COM110E130"]],
                        "next": [["COM112E140", "COM112E150"]]
                    }
                }, { "id": "COM111E140",
                    "name": "IB Computer Science SL Y1",
                    "track": "IB",
                    "level": "SL",
                    "description": "Computer science is the study of computers and computational systems. It covers a range of topics related to the theoretical aspects of computing, including algorithms and software design, and the application of computer science to solve practical problems. Computer science is distinct from the natural sciences in that it does not rely on hypothesis and experimentation. Computer science can be considered to be cross disciplinary, as it draws from a range of disciplines, especially mathematics. The course enables students to:\n• develop conceptual understanding that allows connections to be made between different areas of the subject, and to other DP subjects\n• acquire and apply a body of knowledge, methods, tools and techniques that characterize computer science\n• analyse and evaluate solutions developed through computational thinking in a range of contexts\n• approach unfamiliar situations with creativity and resilience\n• use computational thinking to design and implement solutions to local and global problems\n• develop an appreciation of the possibilities and limitations of computer science\n• evaluate the impact of emerging technologies in computer science\n• communicate and collaborate effectively\n• develop awareness of the environmental, economic, cultural and social impact of computer science, its applications and ethical implications. \nThe contents of this course come as follows:\n• Theme A: Concepts of computer science\n  A1 Computer fundamentals\n  A2 Networks\n  A3 Databases\n  A4 Machine learning\n• Theme B: Computational thinking and problem-solving\n  B1 Computational thinking\n  B2 Programming\n  B3 Object-oriented programming\n• Case study\n• Internal assessment\n  The computational solution\n• Collaborative sciences project\nHomework Expectation: 4-5 hours per week",
                    "rules": {
                        "pre": [["COM110E170", "COM110E130"]],
                        "next": [["COM112E140"]]
                    }
                }, { "id": "COM111E150",
                    "name": "IB Computer Science HL Y1",
                    "track": "IB",
                    "level": "HL",
                    "description": "Computer science is the study of computers and computational systems. It covers a range of topics related to the theoretical aspects of computing, including algorithms and software design, and the application of computer science to solve practical problems. Computer science is distinct from the natural sciences in that it does not rely on hypothesis and experimentation. Computer science can be considered to be cross disciplinary, as it draws from a range of disciplines, especially mathematics. The course enables students to:\n• develop conceptual understanding that allows connections to be made between different areas of the subject, and to other DP subjects\n• acquire and apply a body of knowledge, methods, tools and techniques that characterize computer science\n• analyse and evaluate solutions developed through computational thinking in a range of contexts\n• approach unfamiliar situations with creativity and resilience\n• use computational thinking to design and implement solutions to local and global problems\n• develop an appreciation of the possibilities and limitations of computer science\n• evaluate the impact of emerging technologies in computer science\n• communicate and collaborate effectively\n• develop awareness of the environmental, economic, cultural and social impact of computer science, its applications and ethical implications. \nThe contents of this course come as follows:\n• Theme A: Concepts of computer science\n  A1 Computer fundamentals\n  A2 Networks\n  A3 Databases\n  A4 Machine learning\n• Theme B: Computational thinking and problem-solving\n  B1 Computational thinking\n  B2 Programming\n  B3 Object-oriented programming\n  B4 Abstract data types—HL only\n• Case study\n• Internal assessment\n  The computational solution\n• Collaborative sciences project\nHomework Expectation: 4-5 hours per week",
                    "rules": {
                        "pre": [["COM110E170", "COM110E130"]],
                        "next": [["COM112E150"]]
                    }
                }, { "id": "COM111E100",
                    "name": "Computer Skills 11",
                    "track": "school",
                    "description": "The Computer Skills course is designed to equip students with essential computational knowledge and practical skills required in today’s information-driven society. This course aims to help students build a solid foundation in computer fundamentals and develop confidence in using computational tools effectively. Throughout the course, students will learn basic computer theory, common forms of data representation and processing, and practical problem-solving skills using computers. In addition, the course introduces fundamental Python programming, enabling students to develop basic computational thinking and to prepare for future university-level study and research where programming skills are increasingly required. In response to the rapid development of artificial intelligence, the course also introduces students to AI concepts, principles, and applications. Students will learn how to responsibly and effectively use AI tools, understand their basic working mechanisms, and explore how AI can support learning, research, and real-world problem solving. By the end of the course, students will be able to use computers as effective tools for study, research, and practical tasks, and will be better prepared to adapt to the digital and computational demands of higher education and future careers.\nThe contents of this course come as follows:\n• Computer fundamentals and basic computer theory\n• Data representation and basic data processing methods\n• Introduction to computer networks\n• Introduction to Python programming and computational thinking\n• Practical applications of Python in data processing and problem solving\n• Introduction to artificial intelligence: concepts, principles, and real-world applications\n• Responsible use of AI tools, computer ethics, and digital safety\nHomework Expectation: 2-3 hours per week",
                    "rules": { "next": [["COM112E100"]] }
                }
            ], "12": [
