        }, "english": {
            "9": [
                {   "id": "ENG009S110",
                    "name": "English 9 Standard",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "S",
                    "description": "This introductory course follows the path of higher levels, but relies on excerpts and shorter works. We begin with the classical archetypes of Greco-Roman myth, where students will read Homer, learn the fundamentals of drama in Romeo and Juliet, then embark on an understanding of Jude-Christian symbols. From the 19th century, students are introduced to historicism through such writers as Edgar Allan Poe and Arthur Conan Doyle. In the second half of the course, students hone the skill of a Marxist reading through Modern fiction and the poetry of the Harlem Renaissance setting up a transition into non-fiction texts and current events. The focus on literature in this level is balanced with attention to basic grammar and writing skills. Homework Expectation: 3-4 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "next": [["ENG010S110", "ENG010S120"]] }
                }, { "id": "ENG009S120",
                    "name": "English 9 S+",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "S+",
                    "description": "This introductory course follows the path of higher levels, but relies on shorter works or those of less complexity than honors levels. We begin with the classical archetypes of Greco-Roman myth, where students will read Homer, learn the fundamentals of drama in Romeo and Juliet, then embark on an understanding of Jude-Christian symbols. From the 19th century, students are introduced to the historicism through Victorian literature. In the second half of the course, students perform a Marxist reading of John Steinbeck and hone close reading skills through the poetry of the Harlem Renaissance setting up a transition into the rhetoric of the Civil Rights Movement in the 1960s. The focus on literature in this level is balanced with attention to essay writing and organization. Homework Expectation: 3-4 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "next": [["ENG010S120", "ENG010F130"]] }
                }, { "id": "ENG009F130",
                    "name": "English 9 Honors",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "H",
                    "description": "This introductory course begins with the classical archetypes of Greco-Roman myth through Homer and Ovid, then explores the definition of tragedy through the English Renaissance and Shakespeare's Romeo and Juliet. Students then embark on an understanding of the Judeo-Christian symbols of the Medieval Period. Students will see the arc of literature as it moves out of the Neoclassical period and arrives in the 19th Century where the modern novel is born from such greats as Charles Dickens. In the second half of the course, students are introduced to Modernist literature through a Marxist reading of John Steinbeck's novels and the contemporary period of the Harlem Renaissance setting up a transition into the rhetoric of the Civil Rights Movement in the 1960s. Focus is on interpretation and analysis. Homework Expectation: 5-6 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "next": [["ENG010F130", "ENG010F131"]] }
                }, { "id": "ENG009F131",
                    "name": "English 9 H+",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "H+",
                    "description": "This introductory course begins with the classical archetypes of Greco-Roman myth, where students will read Homer and Ovid's Metamorphoses, then explores Aristotle's definition of tragedy from his Poetics before reaching the English Renaissance and Shakespeare in the 1600s. Next we embark on an understanding of the Judeo-Christian symbols of the Medieval Period and exegetical readings of religious poetry. Students will see the arc of literature as it moves out of the Neoclassical period and arrives in the 19th Century where the modern novel is born from such greats as Jane Austen. In the second half of the course, students are introduced to Marxist and psychoanalytical readings of Modernist literature through John Steinbeck's novels and the contemporary period of the Harlem Renaissance setting up a transition into the rhetoric of the Civil Rights Movement in the 1960s. Focus is on interpretation and analysis through theoretical lenses. Homework Expectation: 5-6 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "next": [["ENG010F131"]] }
                }
            ], "10": [
                {   "id": "ENG010S110",
                    "name": "English 10 Standard",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "S",
                    "description": "This course follows the path of higher levels, but relies on excerpts rather than complete works. We begin with Greek philosophy through excerpts from Plato to give an historical understanding of linguistics before furthering our study of Shakespearean tragedy. Next we consider the role of satire in society and the subversive role of literature. We end the first half of the course with an introduction to narratology and the skills for intertextuality. In the second half of the course, we explore the themes and complexities of Modern and Postmodern literature. Students will also study voices of the world as they encounter literature from different places and cultures. The focus on literature in this level is balanced with attention to basic grammar and writing skills. Homework Expectation: 3-4 hours per week",
