                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "S",
                    "description": "Relying on excerpts and shorter works, this course delves into the founding of the United States through primary source documents and early American writings from the colonial period through the American Revolution. Students will be well prepared for the New SAT by gaining a thorough understanding of the roots of Western democracy, reading the Declaration of Independence, the US Constitution, and key passages from the Federalist Papers. In addition to focuses on writings that reveal the culture and political paradigm of the United States, students continue their focus on English grammar and writing. Homework Expectation: 3-4 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": {
                        "pre": [["ENG010S110"]],
                        "next": [["ENG012S110", "ENG012S120"]]
                    }
                }, { "id": "ENG011S120",
                    "name": "English 11 S+",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "S+",
                    "description": "Relying on shorter works and less complicated texts than its honors counterpart, this course delves into the founding of the United States through primary source documents and early American writings from the colonial period through the American Revolution. Students will be well prepared for the New SAT by gaining a thorough understanding of the roots of Western democracy, reading the Declaration of Independence, the US Constitution, and key passages from the Federalist Papers. From works of the 20th century, we debate the qualities of the American Dream as well as the post-WWII role of the United States. The focus on literature in this level is balanced with attention to essay writing and organization. Homework Expectation: 3-4 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": {
                        "pre": [["ENG010S120"]],
                        "next": [["ENG012S120", "ENG012F130"]]
                    }
                }, { "id": "ENG011F130",
                    "name": "English 11 Honors",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "H",
                    "description": "Relying on longer works and more complicated texts than its standard plus counterpart, this course delves into the founding of the United States through primary source documents and early American writings from the colonial period through the American Revolution. Students will be well prepared for the New SAT by gaining a thorough understanding of the roots of Western democracy, reading the Declaration of Independence, the US Constitution, and key passages from the Federalist Papers. From works of the 20th century, we debate the qualities of the American Dream as well as the post-WWII role of the United States. The focus on literature in this level is on interpretation and analysis. Homework Expectation: 5-6 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": {
                        "pre": [["ENG010F130"]],
                        "next": [["ENG012F130"]]
                    }
                }, { "id": "ENG111E101",
                    "name": "Creative Writing 11",
                    "track": "school",
                    "description": "Creative Writing is designed to give students the opportunity to express their creativity through English writing in a supportive environment. Through a combined academic and studio approach, this course challenges students to create exciting works of art while enhancing their understanding of the craft of fiction. Each month students will be required to submit one original long work for workshopping in class. Tradition and experience hold that workshop experience is an integral part of developing student writing in a supportive critical environment. In addition to workshopping student work in class, every month will center around an anchor text. Students will be required to read at least one essay a month on the craft of writing; this will be accompanied by work from the textbook as well as supplemental works. Students will be tested monthly on their knowledge and understanding of the anchor text and any supplemental texts, as well as on the quality of their response to creative prompts. Homework Expectation: 1-2 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": {
                        "pre": [["ENG010F130"]],
                        "next": [["ENG112E103"]]
                    }
                }, { "id": "ENG011F170",
                    "name": "AP Language and Composition 11",
                    "track": "AP",
                    "description": "This is an advanced English class, which is meant to replace a freshman course at University. The AP English Language and Composition course aligns to an introductory college-level rhetoric and writing curriculum, which requires students to develop evidence-based analytic and argumentative essays that proceed through several stages or drafts. Students evaluate, synthesize, and cite research to support their arguments. Throughout the course, students develop a personal style by making appropriate grammatical choices. Additionally, students read and analyze the rhetorical elements and their effects in non-fiction texts, including graphic images as forms of text, from many disciplines and historical periods. Homework Expectation: 5-6 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": {
                        "pre": [["ENG010F131"]],
                        "next": [["ENG012F170"]]
                    }
                }, { "id": "ENG011F171",
                    "name": "AP Language and Composition Y1",
                    "track": "AP",
                    "description": "This is an advanced English class, which is meant to replace a freshman course at University. The AP English Language and Composition course aligns to an introductory college-level rhetoric and writing curriculum, which requires students to develop evidence-based analytic and argumentative essays that proceed through several stages or drafts. Students evaluate, synthesize, and cite research to support their arguments. Throughout the course, students develop a personal style by making appropriate grammatical choices. Additionally, students read and analyze the rhetorical elements and their effects in non-fiction texts, including graphic images as forms of text, from many disciplines and historical periods. This particular course is for students who need more than one year to prepare for the AP exam. Homework Expectation: 5-6 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": {
                        "pre": [["ENG010F130"]],
                        "next": [["ENG012F171"]]
                    }
                }, { "id": "ENG011F160",
                    "name": "IB English A Literature Y1",
                    "track": "IB",
                    "description": "This is an advanced literature course that will stretch students to become critical readers and confident writers. Through the study of a wide range of literature, this course encourages students to appreciate the artistry of literature and to develop an ability to reflect critically on their reading. Works are studied in their literary and cultural contexts, through close study of individual texts and passages, and by considering a range of critical approaches. The IB English Literature course does not limit the study of works to the products of one culture or the cultures covered by any one language. The study of works in translation is especially important in introducing students, through literature, to other cultural perspectives. The response to the study of literature is through oral and written communication, thus enabling students to develop and refine their command of language. Homework Expectation: 5-6 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": {
                        "pre": [["ENG010F131"]],
                        "next": [["ENG012F160"]]
                    }
                }, { "id": "ENG011F162",
                    "name": "IB English A Language & Literature Y1",
                    "track": "IB",
                    "description": "This is an advanced language and literature course that introduces the critical study and interpretation of written and spoken texts from a wide range of literary forms and non-literary text types. The formal analysis of texts is supplemented by awareness that meaning is not fixed but can change in respect to contexts of production and consumption. The course is organized into three areas of exploration and seven central concepts. Together, the three areas of exploration of the course allow the student to explore the English language through its cultural development and use, its media forms and functions, and its literature. Students develop skills of literary and textual analysis, and also the ability to present their ideas effectively. A key aim is the development of critical literacy. By developing students' ability to speak and write analytically about a wide range of text types, the course offers a broad-based development of the advanced language skills students will apply at the university level. Homework Expectation: 5-6 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": {
                        "pre": [["ENG010F131"]],
                        "next": [["ENG012F162"]]
                    }
                }, { "id": "ENG011F161",
                    "name": "IB English B Language Y1",
                    "track": "IB",
                    "description": "This is an advanced language course that will stretch students to become critical readers and confident writers. IB English Language is an language-learning course designed for students with some previous learning of that language. It may be studied at either SL or HL. The main focus of the course is on language acquisition and development of language skills. These language skills should be developed through the study and use of a range of written and spoken material. Such material will extend from everyday oral exchanges to literary texts, and should be related to the culture(s) concerned. The material should be chosen to enable students to develop mastery of language skills and intercultural understanding. Homework Expectation: 5-6 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": {
                        "pre": [["ENG010F130"]],
                        "next": [["ENG012F161"]]
                    }
                }
            ], "12": [
                {   "id": "ENG012S110",
                    "name": "English 12 Standard",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "S",
                    "description": "Excerpts and shorter works, from the Enlightenment to modern day, with a primary focus on British authors, serve to situate the texts within a broader ideological context. At the onset of the course, students focus on writing for their college admissions essays. In addition to preparation for college applications, the first half of the course studies the legacy of British Colonialism before moving on to texts produced in the 20th century. The focus on literature in this level is balanced with attention to basic grammar and writing skills. Homework Expectation: 3-4 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "pre": [["ENG011S110"]] }
                }, { "id": "ENG012S120",
                    "name": "English 12 S+",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "S+",
                    "description": "Utilizing shorter and less complex works than its honors counterpart, with a primary focus on British authors, this class has the goal of marrying literature and philosophy in order to situate the texts within a broader ideological context. At the onset of the course, students explore the comedy of Shakespeare for a moment of levity before moving on to the Enlightenment to strengthen the tenants behind their college admissions essays. We next study the British Romantics of the 19th Century. The first half of the course closes with an interrogation of the legacy of British Colonialism. In the second half, we focus on texts produced in the 20th century, beginning with Modernism before delving into dystopian fiction and a sampling of international voices. The focus on literature in this level is balanced with attention to essay writing and organization. Homework Expectation: 3-4 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "pre": [["ENG011S120"]] }
                }, { "id": "ENG012F130",
                    "name": "English 12 Honors",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "H",
                    "description": "This course surveys major texts, from the Enlightenment to modern day, with a primary focus on British authors and the goal of marrying literature and philosophy in order to situate the texts within a broader ideological context. At the onset of the course, students explore the comedy of Shakespeare for a moment of levity before moving on to the Enlightenment to strengthen the tenants behind their college admissions essays. We next study the British Romantics of the 19th Century. The first half of the course closes with an interrogation of the legacy of British Colonialism. In the second half, we focus on texts produced in the 20th century, beginning with Modernism such as Virginia Woolf before delving into dystopian fiction of post-WWII and a sampling of international voices. The focus in reading is on interpretation and analysis. Homework Expectation: 5-6 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "pre": [["ENG011F130", "ENG011S120"]] }
                }, { "id": "ENG112E103",
                    "name": "Advanced Creative Writing 12",
                    "track": "school",
                    "description": "Through Stephen King's On Writing as well as dozens of articles, videos, and famous blogs, students will dive deeper into the world of Creative Writing. Though the focus will be on creating works themselves, there will also be time spent on: finding beta readers/how to be a quality beta reader, how to query and when to query literary agents and publishers, the business side of writing (such as writing for a specific market), and what expectations a writer often has versus what expectations are more profitable for the writer. The goals are 1. Submitting Work for Publication/Competitions 2. Enhancing students' ability to express themselves/communicate 3. Exploring new areas of writing while continuing to develop upon the foundation of last year's Creative Writing Class 4. Perfecting essays and personal statements for college applications 5. Providing a creative outlet for students. Homework Expectations: These will generally be writing assignments where either a short work of fiction is created or a longer work of fiction is expanded/revised. In the event of a student interested in another aspect of creative writing (such as playwriting, screenplay writing, and songwriting) other options will be presented so as to feed the passion of the student as opposed to hindering it. In-class assessments will also be given where students' retention of writing styles, structures, and principles learned in class will be tested. Homework Expectation: 1-2 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "pre": [["ENG111E101"]] }
                }, { "id": "ENG012F170",
                    "name": "AP Literature and Composition 12",
                    "track": "AP",
                    "description": "This is an advanced English class, which is meant to replace a freshman course at University. The AP English Literature and Composition course aligns to an introductory college-level literary analysis course. The course engages students in the close reading and critical analysis of imaginative literature to deepen their understanding of the ways writers use language to provide both meaning and pleasure. As they read, students consider a work's structure, style, and themes, as well as its use of figurative language, imagery, symbolism, and tone. Writing assignments include expository, analytical, and argumentative essays that require students to analyze and interpret literary works. Homework Expectation: 5-6 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "pre": [["ENG011F170", "ENG011F171"]] }
                }, { "id": "ENG012F171",
