                        "next": [["GEO111E170"]]
                    }
                }
            ], "11": [
                {   "id": "GEO111E110",
                    "name": "Human Geography 11 Standard",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "S",
                    "description": "This course introduces selected issues of Economic Geography such as green revolution, industrial revolution, urban sprawl and suburbanization, etc. Students at this level need to understand basic concepts and start to interpret spatial distributions of resources, production, and consumption, and of the processes influencing these distributions over time. This course will also briefly introduce some cultural issues that have not been covered in standard tenth-grade class. The learning outcomes related to this course will be assessed through tests, exams, project designing and class participation.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future."
                }, { "id": "GEO111E170",
                    "name": "AP Human Geography 11",
                    "track": "AP",
                    "description": "Those interested in cultural and economic diffusion and how human beings have affected the planet, with a special emphasis on geographic models and maps, will be drawn to the AP Human Geography course. We'll focus on Economic Geography in the first semester as cultural issues have been discussed in tenth-grade class. The course introduces to concepts, approaches and theories that economic geographers use, which will help you understand how they can be applied in the context of the globalizing world economy, and will make you aware of the ways that they affect policy-making. What students take away from the class is a deep understanding of economic geography as a dynamic, diverse and contested body of knowledge that aims to provide critical insights into the workings of contemporary societies and economies. The second semester focuses on a complete review of all seven units for the AP exam, in order to help students better understand and analyze the material they learned in this course. The learning outcomes will be assessed through chapter and unit tests, exams, presentation, group work, paper review, and writing activities.",
