                }, { "id": "HIS009E130",
                    "name": "World History to 1500 9 Honors",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "H",
                    "description": "This course will be taught in a chronological sequence. The focus of this course is the study of the historical development of people, places, and patterns of life from ancient times until 1500 AD. Students will start with Prehistory and move into the earliest civilizations that developed in the River Valleys of Africa, Asia, and Europe. The students will then work their way through the classical civilizations of Egypt, Early India & China, Greece, and Rome. Next, they will study the Middle Ages, the Renaissance, and the Reformation. The class will finish with the Age of Exploration and Conquest. Lectures, readings, assignments, and discussions are designed to offer insights into the cultural, economic, political, religious, and social aspects of human experience. Students will gain an enhanced ability to analyze and evaluate primary and secondary source materials, in order to view history not as a single and fixed narrative but as diverse and shifting narratives based on different perspectives and the interpretation of sources. Homework Expectation: 2-4 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 0.0,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "current": [["MISSING: ENG 9H"]] }
                }
            ], "10": [
                {   "id": "HIS010E110",
                    "name": "World History Since 1500 10 Standard",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "S",
                    "description": "This course will be taught in chronological sequence. This course is a comparative survey of world history as related to the development of the modern world. Students in grade ten study major turning points that shaped the modern world, from the late sixteenth century through the present, including the Age of Enlightenment and Revolution, the Industrial Revolution, the Rise of Imperialism and Colonialism, the cause and course of the two world wars, and the Cold War. They will trace the rise of democratic ideas and develop an understanding of the historical roots of current world issues, especially as they pertain to international relations. Homework Expectation: 2 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 0.0,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "pre": [["HIS009E110"]] }
                }, { "id": "HIS010E120",
                    "name": "World History Since 1500 10 S+",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "S+",
                    "description": "This course will be taught in chronological sequence. This course is a comparative survey of world history as related to the development of the modern world. Students in grade ten study major turning points that shaped the modern world, from the late sixteenth century through the present, including the Age of Enlightenment and Revolution, the Industrial Revolution, the Rise of Imperialism and Colonialism, the cause and course of the two world wars, and the Cold War. Students will emerge from this course with an appreciation and understanding of the world's culture traditions and the process in which these traditions have changed and interacted over time. Students will have the necessary background for further study and preparation for the SAT World History Subject Test. Homework Expectation: 2-3 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 0.0,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "pre": [["HIS009E120"]] }
                }, { "id": "HIS010E130",
                    "name": "World History Since 1500 10 Honors",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "H",
                    "description": "This course will be taught in chronological sequence. Students in grade ten study major turning points that shaped the modern world, from the late sixteenth century through the present, including the Age of Enlightenment and Revolution, the Industrial Revolution, the Rise of Imperialism and Colonialism, the cause and course of the two world wars, and the Cold War. This course imparts the knowledge expected of the students in the standard World History class with expanded breadth and depth. Students are expected to make strong connections between the events of the past and the historical trends of today. An understanding of the information at several different levels is expected. Students will also be charged with projects and papers that expand their learning into activities that prepare them for advanced history classes in the future. Homework Expectation: 2-4 hours per week",
