                    }
                }
            ], "11": [
                {   "id": "HIS111E110",
                    "name": "United States Overview 11 Standard",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "S",
                    "description": "This history course examines the rich cultural, economic, historical, and social heritage of the United States as it has developed from the origins of the American Revolution through to major developments in the modern era. This course also focuses on class, gender and racial issues and their significance to U.S. national history, the placement of American history in its global context, and the constant discussion between change and continuity. This course hopes to give students planning to study in the United States a rigorous background in the major institutions and structures of U.S. society and to provide students with essential knowledge and insights to better understand the significant issues that face American society today. Homework Expectation: 2-3 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 0.0,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future."
                }, { "id": "HIS111E130",
                    "name": "United States Overview 11 Honors",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "H",
                    "description": "This history course examines the rich cultural, economic, historical, and social heritage of the United States as it has developed from the origins of the American Revolution through to major developments in the modern era. This course also focuses on class, gender and racial issues and their significance to U.S. national history, the placement of American history in its global context, and the constant discussion between change and continuity. This course hopes to give students planning to study in the United States a rigorous background in the major institutions and structures of U.S. society and to provide students with essential knowledge and insights to better understand the significant issues that face American society today. Additionally, the course will integrate a chronological and thematic study of the significant cultural, economic, historical, and social issues encountered by the United States. Each unit will focus on important cultural, economic, historical, and social events that have shaped the United States government's domestic, economic, and foreign policies during those periods. This course examines the historical and multicultural heritage of the United States, the role of the government in domestic matters and its role in world affairs. Homework Expectation: 3-4 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 0.0,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "current": [["MISSING: ENG 11H"]] }
                }, { "id": "HIS111E111",
                    "name": "Traditional China: History and Culture 11 Standard",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "S",
                    "description": "This course will look chronologically at the foundation, development, and maturity of Chinese civilization ranging from its origins through the end of the Qing Dynasty. The course will focus on the themes of political institutions and developments (including the function of the Imperial system and the role of the Scholar-gentry), the role and status of women in society, the development and function of the economy and trade, the growth and development of ideas, schools, and religion (with a particular emphasis on Confucianism, Legalism, Daoism, Buddhism, and Neo-Confucianism), the development of cities, the role and effects of geography, social class, family, and hierarchy, technological developments, culture, the relationship with surrounding peoples, travelers (exp. Xuanzang), encounters with other civilizations, and the growth of overseas Chinese communities. In addition the notion of Han identity will be explored in relation to the growth and development of the consolidation and development of Chinese civilization. The course will have a particular emphasis on primary sources in English-language translation (ranging from art to poetry to philosophy and religion). In additional specific Chinese painters, poets, scientists, political, cultural figures and thinkers will be considered for more detailed study within each period we consider. This will include such figures as Sun Wu, Wang Wei, Du Fu, and Li Bai. Students will be responsible for several written assignments, at least one fully researched and developed essay, and a significant project each semester focusing on a detailed study of one or more of the course themes.The teaching language is chinese. Homework Expectation: 2 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 0.0,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "current": [["MISSING: CHINESE NATIVE"]] }
                }, { "id": "HIS111E131",
                    "name": "Traditional China: History and Culture 11 Honors",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "H",
                    "description": "This course will look chronologically at the foundation, development, and maturity of Chinese civilization ranging from its origins through the end of the Qing Dynasty. The course will focus on the themes of political institutions and developments (including the function of the Imperial system and the role of the Scholar-gentry), the role and status of women in society, the development and function of the economy and trade, the growth and development of ideas, schools, and religion (with a particular emphasis on Confucianism, Legalism, Daoism, Buddhism, and Neo-Confucianism), the development of cities, the role and effects of geography, social class, family, and hierarchy, technological developments, culture, the relationship with surrounding peoples, travelers (exp. Xuanzang), encounters with other civilizations, and the growth of overseas Chinese communities. In addition the notion of Han identity will be explored in relation to the growth and development of the consolidation and development of Chinese civilization. The course will have a particular emphasis on primary sources in English-language translation (ranging from art to poetry to philosophy and religion). In additional specific Chinese painters, poets, scientists, political, cultural figures and thinkers will be considered for more detailed study within each period we consider. This will include such figures as Sun Wu, Wang Wei, Du Fu, and Li Bai. Students will be responsible for several written assignments, at least one fully researched and developed essay, and a significant project each semester focusing on a detailed study of one or more of the course themes.The teaching language is chinese. Homework Expectation: 3-4 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 0.0,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "current": [["MISSING: CHINESE NATIVE H"]] }
                }, { "id": "HIS111E112",
                    "name": "Western Civilization 1 11 Standard",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "S",
                    "description": "This course develops an understanding of the connectivity of Modern Western Society to its historical and cultural foundations. Topics include ancient Greece, Rome, Christianity, Judaism, Renaissance and Exploration. Students will develop a basic understanding of each major themes and basic analysis and writting skills. Most importantly students will recognize that the study of Western society and culture is a living history, one that is changing but always connected to the past. Homework Expectation: 2 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 0.0,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "next": [["HIS112E110"]] }
                }, { "id": "HIS111E132",
                    "name": "Western Civilization 1 11 Honors",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "H",
                    "description": "This course develops an understanding of the connectivity of Modern Western Society to its historical and cultural foundations. Topics include ancient Greece, Rome, Christianity, Judaism, Renaissance and Exploration. Various historical skills of interpretation, analysis, writting shall be emphasized. The course will incorporate primary source reading, critical analysis and discussion of Western Philosophy. Upon completion, students should be able to analyze significant political, socioeconomic, and cultural developments in western civilization.The course that prepares students to take higher level critical thinking courses in colleges or universities. Homework Expectation: 3-4 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 0.0,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": {
                        "current": [["MISSING: ENG 11H"]], 
                        "next": [["HIS112E130"]]
                    }
                }, { "id": "HIS111E160",
                    "name": "IB World History SL/HL Y1",
                    "track": "IB",
                    "description": "This course is intended to prepare IBDP and IBCP students, at both standard and high levels, for the International Baccalaureate exam in History. Standard-level students have multiple topics to study within the Paper 1 and Paper 2 topics. The primary focus for both papers is 19th-20th century history, particularly the Cold War. Additionally, High-level students will complete Paper 3, choosing from various regional topics that primarily focus on Europe, Africa, or the Americas. The 11th-grade year is focused on the acquisition of content knowledge (a majority of both paper 2 topics should be covered) and in familiarizing students with the IB History assessment format and criteria along with key historical skills. The specific skills focus for SL and HL students is on the construction of analytic thesis essays that address the requirements of the IB assessment mark scheme, document analysis skills, reading strategies, and issues of historiography. Homework Expectation: 3-5 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 0.0,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": {
                        "pre": [["HIS010E130", "HIS110E170"]], 
                        "current": [["MISSING: ENG 11H"]], 
                        "next": [["HIS112E160"]]
                    }
                }, { "id": "PHI111E140",
                    "name": "IB Philosophy SL Y1",
                    "track": "IB",
                    "level": "SL",
                    "description": "This course is taught with the assumption you have not studied philosophy before and begins with an introduction unit. Philosophy is an inquiry into profound, fascinating and challenging questions such as: What is it to be human? Do we have free will? What is right or wrong? These abstract questions arise out of our everyday experiences, and philosophical tools such as critical and systematic thinking, careful analysis, and construction of arguments provide the means of addressing such questions. The focus of the course is on doing philosophy, which means developing your opinion and your argument is the focus of the class. Students will study the core theme of being human, which includes topics from human nature to identity, students will also consider ethical dilemmas and thought experiments. In addition, one short text must be studied for paper 2, the Meditations by Rene Descartes. You will also write an internal assessment (IA) on a non-philosophical stimulus such as a movie or TV episode and analyse it using philosophical skills. Classes will focus on inquiry and discussion, across the course, you will also develop skills in logic and argumentation. The IB Philosophy curriculum is flexible, allowing students to study the philosophers they are most interested in. Homework Expectation: 1-2 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 0.0,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": {
                        "current": [["MISSING: ENG 11H+"]], 
                        "next": [["PHI112E140"]]
                    }
                }, { "id": "HIS111E171",
                    "name": "AP US History 11",
                    "track": "AP",
                    "description": "Students in Advanced Placement history will be engaging in a demanding course that will expect them to apply historical skills to a new content area. This course will begin with Pre-Colombian societies in the Americas. The course will cover the Colonial Period and Revolution prior to the first midterm. The course will then cover the periods leading up to the Civil and Reconstruction. The Second Semester will conclude that major topics in the remaining decades of the 19th century including industrialization and the emergence of big business. The second unit will discuss the various reform movements and the period leading up to World War One. The other major units will discuss the Great Depression and the New Deal, the Cold War and the politics associated with it. There will be an additional focus on the Civil Rights movement and the state of affairs for Native Americans. This course will conclude with a review of the course content in preparation for the AP exam in May. Homework Expectation: 4-6 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 0.0,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
