                    "name": "AP Art History 11",
                    "track": "AP",
                    "description": "Advanced Placement Art History is designed as an introductory survey course to the discipline of Art History. The course will strictly adhere to the Course and Exam Description published by the College Board, which requires knowledge of 250 distinct works of art, divided across 10 units of study. The first semester will explore the following periods and geographic locations: Prehistoric; Ancient Mediterranean; Early Europe and Colonial Americas; Later Europe and Colonial Americas; and Indigenous Americas. The second semester will explore the following: Africa; Central and Western Asia; South, East and Southeast Asia; the Pacific; and Global Contemporary. Skills developed include visual analysis, contextual analysis, continuity and change, comparison, and attribution. These skills will be assessed frequently with essays (long and short), as well as multiple choice questions. Homework Expectation: 4-6 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 0.0,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": {
                        "pre": [["HIS010E120", "HIS010E130", "HIS110E170"]], 
                        "current": [["MISSING: ENG 10H"]]
                    }
                }, { "id": "PHI111E100",
                    "name": "Philosophy 11",
                    "track": "school",
                    "description": "The philosophy school course is taught with the assumption you have not studied philosophy before, the course begins with an introduction unit. Philosophy is one of the oldest subjects and is prized by top universities for its emphasis on critical thinking skills and logical thinking. Students are trained 'to do philosophy' that means your opinion and honing your argument is what matters! The course uses thought experiments, ethical dilemmas and grounds these discussions in popular culture like film. For example, we explore questions raised in sci-fi shows like Star Trek about the rights of robots or AI. You will study human nature, identity, philosophy of mind, and consciousness, as well as answer questions such as \"Do I have free will?\", and ethical questions about right and wrong, and answer the question \"How do we know what I think I know?\". A variety of assessments will be used including creative projects and short essays. For example, the semester 1 philosophy comic creation project. The class is student-centred and focuses on students developing their own voice, as well as developing their critical argumentative skills. This course would be suitable for students hoping to, express their point of view, and improve their critical, argumentative, and analytical skills, as well as their independent research skills. Homework Expectation: 1-2 hours per week",
