                    }
                }, { "id": "HIS112E111",
                    "name": "American Government and Politics 12 Standard",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "S",
                    "description": "This class will introduce students to the basic components of the American system of government. The first unit will discuss the Constitutional foundations of the government. The second unit will consider beliefs and behaviors regarding government. The third unit will look at political parties and the role of the media. The fourth unit will look at the legislative, judicial and executive branches of the government. The last unit will discuss civil rights and liberties in the United States. This class is designed to be a survey course in American government and it will allow students to have a better understanding of many aspects of American history. This class would work well for students who plan to take US History in grade 12. Homework Expectation: 2 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 0.0,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future."
                }, { "id": "HIS112E131",
                    "name": "American Government and Politics 12 Honors",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "H",
                    "description": "This class will introduce students to the basic components of the American system of government. The first unit will discuss the Constitutional foundations of the government. The second unit will consider beliefs and behaviors regarding government. The third unit will look at various court cases and analyze their impact on America. The last unit will discuss civil rights and liberties in America. This class is designed to be a survey course in American government and it will allow students to have a better understanding of many aspects of American history. This class would work well for students who plan to go to the United States for university providing them with a good understanding of the country they will be moving to. Homework Expectation: 3-4 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 0.0,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "current": [["MISSING: ENG 12H"]] }
                }, { "id": "HIS112E160",
                    "name": "IB World History SL/HL Y2",
                    "track": "IB",
                    "description": "This course is intended to prepare IBDP and IBCP students, at both standard and high levels, for the International Baccalaureate exam in History. Standard-level students have multiple topics to study within the Paper 1 and Paper 2 topics. The primary focus for both papers is 19th-20th century history, particularly the Cold War. Additionally, High-level students choose from various regional topics that primarily focus on Europe, Africa, or the Americas. 12th Grade IB History students complete the study of all topics by the final exam. At least one month should be given to review and practice the essay topics and for students to refine their IA drafts. Activities and assessments should focus on the further development of individual strategies for Papers 1, 2, and 3. Students will have approximately two months to review prior to the IB exam, though review assignments such as essays and readings should be placed throughout the year. Homework Expectation: 3-5 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 0.0,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "pre": [["HIS111E160"]] }
                }, { "id": "PHI112E140",
                    "name": "IB Philosophy SL Y2",
                    "track": "IB",
                    "level": "SL",
                    "description": "This course is taught with the assumption you have not studied philosophy before and begins with an introduction unit. Philosophy is an inquiry into profound, fascinating and challenging questions such as: What is it to be human? Do we have free will? What is right or wrong? These abstract questions arise out of our everyday experiences, and philosophical tools such as critical and systematic thinking, careful analysis, and construction of arguments provide the means of addressing such questions. The focus of the course is on doing philosophy, which means developing your opinion and your argument is the focus of the class. Students will study the core theme of being human, which includes topics from human nature to identity, students will also consider ethical dilemmas and thought experiments. In addition, one short text must be studied for paper 2, the Meditations by Rene Descartes. You will also write an internal assessment (IA) on a non-philosophical stimulus such as a movie or TV episode and analyse it using philosophical skills. Classes will focus on inquiry and discussion, across the course, you will also develop skills in logic and argumentation. The IB Philosophy curriculum is flexible, allowing students to study the philosophers they are most interested in. Homework Expectation: 1-2 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 0.0,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "pre": [["PHI111E140"]] }
                }, { "id": "HIS112E171",
                    "name": "AP US History 12",
                    "track": "AP",
                    "description": "Students in Advanced Placement history will be engaging in a demanding course that will expect them to apply historical skills to a new content area. This course will begin with Pre-Colombian societies in the Americas. The course will cover the Colonial Period and Revolution prior to the first midterm. The course will then cover the periods leading up to the Civil and Reconstruction. The Second Semester will conclude that major topics in the remaining decades of the 19th century including industrialization and the emergence of big business. The second unit will discuss the various reform movements and the period leading up to World War One. The other major units will discuss the Great Depression and the New Deal, the Cold War and the politics associated with it. There will be an additional focus on the Civil Rights movement and the state of affairs for Native Americans. This course will conclude with a review of the course content in preparation for the AP exam in May. Homework Expectation: 4-6 hours per week",
                    "crowdRating": 0.0,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": {
