        }, "math": {
            "9": [
                {   "id": "MAT009E91GE",
                    "name": "Geometry 9 Standard",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "S",
                    "description": "Designed for students in Grade 9, this course aims to foster geometric intuition and develop fundamental logical reasoning abilities. The main geometric content includes the tools of geometry, simple reasoning and proof, basic 2-D geometric figures, transformations, and measuring in the plane and space. 2-D figures cover lines, triangles, quadrilaterals, and circles. To broaden students’ problem-solving perspectives, elements of algorithmic thinking will be interspersed throughout the course. This includes introducing illustrative methods such as the Monte Carlo technique in relevant geometric and measurement contexts, helping students connect mathematical concepts with computational approaches. A dedicated module on foundational data analysis skills will also be included, providing focused exposure to the principles and tools of statistical reasoning. In the Geometric Standard course, students will apply basic geometric concepts with an emphasis on practical applications rather than formal proofs. After one year of study, students are expected to: Master the properties of basic 2D shapes; Perform spatial visualization and composition; Solve real-world problems using visual and spatial reasoning; Gain exposure to algorithmic strategies for exploring mathematical ideas; Develop a preliminary understanding of statistical thinking and its differences from classical mathematical operations. This course serves as preparation for Pre-calculus Standard in the following year.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "next": [["MAT010E91PC"]] }
                }, { "id": "MAT009E92GE",
                    "name": "Geometry 9 S+",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "S+",
                    "description": "Designed for students in Grade 9, this course aims to foster geometric intuition and develop fundamental logical reasoning abilities. The main geometric content includes the tools of geometry, reasoning and proof, 2-D geometric figures, transformations, as well as measuring in the plane and space. 2-D geometric figures encompass lines, triangles, quadrilaterals, and circles. To provide a wider perspective on problem-solving, elements of algorithmic thinking will be introduced periodically throughout the course. This includes exploring methods like the Monte Carlo technique in contexts such as estimation and measurement, allowing students to connect geometric concepts with accessible computational approaches. A dedicated module on foundational data analysis skills will also be provided, giving students a focused introduction to the tools and logic of statistical reasoning. In the Geometry S+ course, students will apply the concepts of geometry with an emphasis on practical applications, while also performing some formal geometric proofs. After one year of study, students are expected to: Master the properties of 2D graphics; Perform spatial imagination and composition; Solve real-world problems using visualization and spatial reasoning; Gain exposure to simple algorithmic strategies for investigating mathematical ideas; Develop a preliminary understanding of the differences between statistical thinking and classical mathematical operations. It’s a preparation for Pre-calculus H the following year.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "next": [["MAT010E93PC"]] }
                }, { "id": "MAT009E93GE",
                    "name": "Geometry 9 Honors",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "H",
                    "description": "Designed for Grade 9 students, this course aims to foster geometric intuition and logical reasoning abilities. The main geometric content includes the tools of geometry, reasoning and proof, 2-D geometric figures, some basic 3-D geometric figures, transformations, as well as measuring in the plane and space. 2-D geometric figures comprise lines, triangles, quadrilaterals, and circles. 3-D figures include planes, prisms, cylinders, spheres, and conics. Algorithmic thinking will be woven into relevant topics across the course, allowing students to engage with more sophisticated computational strategies. For example, they may implement or simulate Monte Carlo methods to explore geometric probability, connecting deeper mathematical concepts with analytical problem-solving techniques. A concentrated unit on data analysis skills will also be integrated, enabling students to gain a clear and structured understanding of statistical reasoning and its distinction from classical mathematical operations. In the Geometry HL, students are expected to use inductive and deductive reasoning to develop mathematical arguments, and to analyze characteristics and properties of 2-D and 3-D figures. Coordinate geometry is used as an efficient tool when describing spatial relationships and solving problems. The ability to solve real-world problems using visualization and spatial reasoning is essential for H students. After one year of study, students will also be expected to: Apply algorithmic approaches to investigate and validate geometric relationships; Clearly distinguish between statistical thinking and classical mathematical operations; Demonstrate readiness for the analytical challenges of AP Pre-calculus. It’s a preparation for AP Pre-calculus the following year.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "next": [["MAT010E50PC"]] }
                }, { "id": "MAT009E94GE",
                    "name": "Geometry 9 H+",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "H+",
                    "description": "Based on Honors level, the school offers the H+ course for students with exceptional learning abilities and intentions. The H+ course aims to foster students' independence, innovation, and intelligence. Hybrid learning and flipped classrooms will be the norm. Students should become self-directed learners, while teachers function as motivators and providers of necessary guidance and support. In terms of teaching content, in addition to regular Honors content, competition-style questions and pre-calculus content will also be integrated. Algorithmic thinking and problem-solving strategies will be explored within advanced geometric contexts to further enhance analytical skills. After one year of study, H+ students not only need to develop excellent geometric abilities, including strong spatial intuition, geometric proof skills, and the ability to use geometric models to solve problems, but also need to master statistical thinking in data analysis. Additionally, they need to establish a solid foundation in precalculus to prepare for AP calculus the following year. Students will also be expected to apply algorithmic strategies to validate solutions and approach open-ended mathematical questions. The pace of learning is rapid, but after a year of challenges, students will reap significant benefits.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "next": [["MAT010E50CL"]] }
                }
            ], "10": [
                {   "id": "MAT010E91PC",
                    "name": "Pre-calculus 10 Standard",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "S",
                    "description": "This course is designed to prepare students for advanced mathematics and calculus. In this course, some of the necessary algebra skills and basic functions from Algebra I are reviewed and some new functions, including polynomials, rational functions, exponential and logarithmic functions, as well as trigonometry, will be discussed. The primary purpose is to develop a better understanding of functions and their applications, numerically, graphically and analytically. All students are expected to be prepared for study of Calculus in grade 11. Additionally, to bridge mathematics with real-world applications, key algorithmic concepts—such as Bisection Method, Euclidean Algorithm, Greedy Algorithm, and Dynamic Programming—will be introduced within the 10th-grade pre-calculus curriculum.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": {
                        "pre": [["MAT009E91GE"]],
                        "next": [["MAT011E91CL"]]
                    }
                }, { "id": "MAT010E93PC",
                    "name": "Pre-calculus 10 Honors",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "H",
                    "description": "This course is designed to better prepare students for calculus or advanced mathematics. In this course, some of the necessary algebra skills are reviewed and some new concepts, such as polynomials, rational functions, exponential and logarithmic functions as well as trigonometry, will be discussed. The course also covers how to graph the aforementioned various functions. The primary purpose is to develop an understanding of the basic functions and their applications. The use of graphing technology is integrated into the course material and is employed extensively to help students visualize solutions. All students are expected to develop the ability of self-study and have the opportunities to communicate mathematical ideas in words, both orally and in writing to improve the notational fluency. Additionally, students in the 10th-grade pre-calculus curriculum will learn key algorithmic concepts—including the Bisection Method, Euclidean Algorithm, Greedy Algorithm, and Dynamic Programming—to bridge mathematics with real-world applications and to enhance problem-solving skills.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": {
                        "pre": [["MAT009E92GE"]],
                        "next": [["MAT011E93CL", "MAT011E51CL"]]
                    }
                }, { "id": "MAT010E50PC",
                    "name": "AP Precalculus 10",
                    "track": "AP",
                    "description": "AP Precalculus focuses on developing a comprehensive understanding of functions through multiple representations: graphical, numerical, analytical, and verbal. The course covers core function families, including polynomial, rational, exponential, logarithmic, trigonometric, and polar functions, as well as functions involving parameters, vectors, and matrices. Students explore compositions, inverses, and transformations to analyze function behaviors in both mathematical and real-world contexts. This enriched scope is further enhanced by integrating key algorithmic concepts—such as the Bisection Method, Euclidean Algorithm, Greedy Algorithm, and Dynamic Programming. These concepts bridge abstract mathematics with applied problem-solving, strengthening analytical reasoning and ensuring students are well-prepared for advanced mathematical studies such as AP Calculus, IB Mathematics, or AP Statistics.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": {
                        "pre": [["MAT009E93GE"]],
                        "next": [["MAT011E51CL", "MAT011E53CL", "MAT011E50ST", "MAT011E73AA", "MAT011E73AI"]]
                    }
                }, { "id": "MAT010E50CL",
                    "name": "AP Calculus 10",
                    "track": "AP",
                    "description": "In Grade 10, this course is intended for highly prepared students only. As a sequel to Geometry H+, it aims to foster students' autonomy, creativity, and analytical thinking through hybrid learning and flipped classrooms. The curriculum covers core calculus topics, including limits, derivatives, integrals, applications of derivatives and integrals, differential equations and mathematical modeling, as well as polynomial approximations and series. To deepen the connection between continuous mathematics, discrete computational thinking, and real-world modeling, the course also introduces foundational numerical methods and algorithmic concepts—such as the Bisection and Newton’s Methods for root-finding, Euler’s Method for differential equations, and the formal study of optimization paradigms including greedy algorithm. This integration strengthens students’ ability to translate complex problems into solvable mathematical forms and execute solution strategies both analytically and computationally. Upon completion, students will understand these topics algebraically, numerically, graphically, and verbally, and take the AP Calculus BC exam. Beyond exam preparation, students further develop application, communication, and reflective skills by using calculus as a tool for independent exploration. After one year, students are strongly encouraged to continue into IB mathematics.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": {
                        "pre": [["MAT009E94GE"]],
                        "next": [["MAT011E73AA", "MAT011E73AI"]]
                    }
                }
            ], "11": [
