                        "next": [["MAT012E71AI"]]
                    }
                }, { "id": "MAT011E73AI",
                    "name": "IB Mathematics: Applications and Interpretation HL Y1",
                    "track": "IB",
                    "level": "HL",
                    "description": "This course is intended for students who plan to pursue subjects such as social sciences, natural sciences, statistics, business, some economics, psychology, and design. Given that mathematics is a sequential subject, it is required that students enrolling in the Diploma Program (DP) Mathematics: Applications and Interpretation HL course will have easily and successfully completed AP Calculus or AP Pre-calculus in grade 10, and possess strong English proficiency. This course emphasizes the applied nature of mathematics, and also that interpretation of results in context is an important element of this course. It will develop students’ mathematics for describing our world and solving practical problems. Students will harness the power of technology alongside exploring mathematical models. The aims of this course are to develop students’ abilities in communication, critical thinking, generalization, problem-solving, etc. There are 6 content sections, as listed below. Of them, sections 4 and 5 are the key sections. 1. Numbers and algebra; 2. Functions; 3. Trigonometry and geometry; 4. Statistics and probability; 5. Calculus; 6. “Toolkit” and IA. Students will take IB Mathematics: Applications and Interpretation HL Exam after the course.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": {
                        "pre": [["MAT010E50PC", "MAT010E50CL"]],
                        "next": [["MAT012E73AI"]]
                    }
                }, { "id": "MAT011E10AL",
                    "name": "A-Level Math AS",
                    "track": "ASA2",
                    "level": "AS",
                    "description": "This is a college-level course designed to help students who intend to take A-level math qualifications (Oxford AQA, including AS and A2 level) in 11th and 12th grade. Core contents include pure mathematics, statistics, and mechanics. Emphasis is on problem-solving skills. The aims are to enable students to develop their mathematical knowledge and skills in a way that encourages confidence and provides satisfaction and enjoyment. Students will acquire a range of mathematical skills, including the use of applications of mathematics in the context of everyday situations and in other subjects that they may be studying, and they will also acquire the mathematical background necessary for further study in this or related subjects. After learning this course, students should be able to understand the above topics algebraically, numerically, logically. Students will take AS and A2 level exam after the course.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": {
                        "pre": [["MAT010E93PC", "MAT010E50PC"]],
                        "next": [["MAT012E10AL"]]
                    }
                }, { "id": "MAT011E10FM",
                    "name": "A-Level Further Mathematics AS",
                    "track": "ASA2",
                    "level": "AS",
                    "description": "This course is designed for students seeking to delve deeper into mathematics and challenge themselves in preparation for a mathematics-related degree. This is an optional math course and cannot replace the A-level math course. Students must possess a solid foundation in Pre-calculus and have the ability to perform well in A-Level Math courses. An above-average performance in Pre-calculus H is preferred. This course is designed to help students who intend to take Oxford AQA International Further Mathematics qualifications which consist of four units over two years based on three core topics: Pure Mathematics, Statistics and Mechanics. Pure Math part includes algebra and graphs, coordinate geometry, complex numbers, roots and coefficients of a quadratic equation, trigonometry, calculus, matrices and transformations, linear graphs, numerical methods, roots and polynomials, De Moivre’s Theorem, polar coordinates, proof by induction, finite series, hyperbolic functions, differential equations, vectors and matrix algebra. Statistics part includes Bayes’ Theorem, uniform distribution, geometric distribution, probability generating functions, linear combinations of discrete random variables, moment generating functions, estimators, estimation and further hypothesis testing. Mechanics part includes constant velocity in two dimensions, dimensional analysis, collisions in one dimension, vertical circular motion, projectiles launched onto inclined planes, elastic strings and springs, collisions in two dimensions, application of differential equations and simple harmonic motion. The course aims to encourage students to develop their abilities to reason logically and to recognize incorrect reasoning, to generalize and to construct problems. Students will extend their range of mathematical skills and techniques and use them in more difficult unstructured problems as well as develop an understanding of coherence and progression in mathematics and how different areas of mathematics can be connected.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": {
                        "pre": [["MAT010E93PC", "MAT010E50PC"]],
                        "next": [["MAT012E10FM"]]
                    }
                }
            ], "12": [
                {   "id": "MAT012E91AM",
                    "name": "Advanced Mathematics 12 Standard",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "S",
                    "description": "The course is designed for students at S level in Grade 12. Its main contents are polar coordinates and complex numbers, vectors and determinants, matrices, combinatorics, probability, statistics, and curve fitting and models. After this course, students are expected to have wider recognitions of math other than algebra and geometry. They are expected to realize that: there are different types of coordinate systems; there are different types of multiplications between vectors and between matrices; probability is different from percentage; good interpretation of data could help us make wise decisions. Application of math is an important teaching objective.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "pre": [["MAT011E91CL"]] }
                }, { "id": "MAT012E93AM",
                    "name": "Advanced Mathematics 12 Honors",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "H",
                    "description": "The course is designed for students at H level in Grade 12. Its main contents are analytic geometry polar coordinates and complex numbers, vectors and determinants, matrices, combinatorics, probability, statistics, and curve fitting and models. Compared with S level, although the same studying procedure has been used, students are expected to show precision and flexibility when solving problems. Modeling and problem-solving are still central to learning Advanced Mathematics H. After this course, students are expected to have wider recognition of math other than algebra and geometry. And they are expected to wisely apply what they have learned to solve problems arising in everyday life, society and workplace.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "pre": [["MAT011E93CL", "MAT011E51CL", "MAT011E53CL"]] }
                }, { "id": "MAT012E93FM",
                    "name": "Further Mathematics 12 Honors",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "H",
                    "description": "This course is designed specifically to allow students to focus on different branches of mathematics, and to encourage students to appreciate the diversity of mathematics. It is expected that students embarking on the Further Mathematics course will have successfully finished their Calculus H or AP course in grade 11, and have a particular aptitude and interest in mathematics. Contents: Topic 1: Set theory. Set theory is the branch of mathematical logic that studies sets, which informally are collections of objects. Although any type of object can be collected into a set, set theory is applied most often to objects that are relevant to mathematics. The language of set theory can be used in the definitions of nearly all mathematical objects. Topic 2: Group theory. As the central concept in abstract algebra, groups recur throughout mathematics, and the methods of group theory have influenced many parts of algebra. Thus group theory and the closely related representation theory have many important applications in physics, chemistry, and materials science. It is also central to public key cryptography. Topic 3: Number theory. Number theory is a branch of pure mathematics devoted primarily to the study of the natural numbers and the integers. It is sometimes called \"The Queen of Mathematics\" because of its foundational place in the discipline. Topic 4: Graph theory. In mathematics and computer science, graph theory is the study of graphs, which are mathematical structures used to model pairwise relations between objects. Graphs can be used to model many types of relations and processes in physical, biological, social and information systems. Many practical problems can be represented by graphs. Aims: After learning these theories, students are expected to understand high school math knowledge deeper, appreciate the development of pure and applied mathematics, think about and solve problems in logic and mathematical ways.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "pre": [["MAT011E93CL", "MAT011E51CL", "MAT011E53CL"]] }
                }, { "id": "MAT012E93MC",
                    "name": "Multivariable Calculus 12 Honors",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "H",
                    "description": "Multivariable Calculus course is recommended for students who are strongly interested in Calculus and have a qualified mathematics ability. It is designed to help students explore Calculus deeply. The contents are comprehensive and challenging. Before taking this course, students need to be familiar with single variable calculus contents, such as differentiation and integration formulas and skills, as well as basic methods to solve differential equations. The study of this course includes Parametric Equations and Polar Coordinates, Infinite Sequences and Series, Vectors and the Geometry of Space, Vector Function, Partial Derivatives, Multiple Integrals, Vector Calculus, and Second-Order Differential Equations. These mathematical tools and methods are extensively used in the physical sciences, engineering, economics and computer graphics. After learning this course, students will be able to understand the above topics algebraically, numerically, graphically and verbally.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "pre": [["MAT011E53CL", "MAT011E51CL", "MAT011E93CL"]] }
                }, { "id": "MAT012E93SP",
                    "name": "Statistics in Practice 12 Honors",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "H",
                    "description": "This course is designed for students who completed Calculus H level or an AP course in grade 11 or previous S level students who are able to show a certain level of statistics literacy evaluated by the instructor. Some business knowledge is highly appreciated but not required. The course aims to provide students with a conceptual introduction to the application of statistics, particularly in the field of business, economics and social sciences. As an applications-oriented course, it covers the applications of data analysis and statistical methodology. The discussion and development of each technique is presented in an application setting, with the statistical results providing insights to decision-making and problem-solving. This course also emphasizes the use of computer software in statistical analysis. Leveraging on the idea of project-based learning, it includes case problems related to the topics, giving students the opportunity to work on complex problems, analyze larger data sets, and prepare managerial reports based on real-world analyses. The following are some broad topics covered in this course. Topic 1: Descriptive statistics. Topic 2: Probability and distributions. Topic 3: Statistical Inference (both parametric and nonparametric). Topic 4: Regression analysis, modeling and time series analysis. Topic 5: Sample survey and questionnaire design.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "pre": [["MAT011E93CL", "MAT011E51CL", "MAT011E53CL", "MAT011E50ST"]] }
                }, { "id": "MAT012E50ST",
                    "name": "AP Statistics 12",
                    "track": "AP",
                    "description": "The purpose of the AP course in statistics is to introduce students to the major concepts and tools for collecting, analyzing, and drawing conclusions from data. Students are exposed to four broad conceptual themes: I. Exploring Data: Describing patterns and departures from patterns. Exploratory analysis of data makes use of graphical and numerical techniques to study patterns and departures from patterns. II. Sampling and Experimentation: Planning and conducting a study. Data must be collected according to a well-developed plan if valid information on a conjecture is to be obtained. This plan includes clarifying the question and deciding upon a method of data collection and analysis. III. Anticipating Patterns: Exploring random phenomena using probability and simulation. Probability is the tool used for anticipating what the distribution of data should look like under a given model. IV. Statistical Inference: Estimating population parameters and testing hypotheses. Statistical inference guides the selection of appropriate models. The course follows the outline recommended by the College Board and is designed to enable students to successfully take the College Board Advanced Placement Examination.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": {
                        "pre": [["MAT011E93CL", "MAT011E51CL", "MAT011E53CL"]],
                        "current": [["MISSING: ENG 11H"]]
                    }
                }, { "id": "MAT012E51CL",
                    "name": "AP Calculus AB 12",
                    "track": "AP",
                    "description": "AP Calculus AB introduces topics in calculus. This course is recommended for students who possess advanced mathematics abilities. The topics of study include limits, derivatives, integrals, applications of derivatives and integrals, differential equations and mathematical modeling. After completing this course, students should be able to comprehend the above topics algebraically, numerically, graphically and verbally. Students will take the AP Calculus AB Exam upon finishing the course.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "pre": [["MAT011E50ST"]] }
                }, { "id": "MAT012E71AA",
                    "name": "IB Mathematics: Analysis and Approaches SL Y2",
                    "track": "IB",
                    "level": "SL",
                    "description": "This course is intended for students who plan to pursue subjects with significant mathematical components, such as mathematics itself, engineering, physical sciences, or economics, among others. Given that mathematics is a sequential subject, it is required that students enrolling in the Diploma Program (DP) Mathematics: Analysis and Approaches SL course will have successfully completed AP Calculus or AP Pre-calculus in grade 10. This course reflects the emphasis on calculus and on algebraic, graphical and numerical approaches. It will develop students’ mathematics to become more fluent in the construction of mathematical arguments and develop strong skills in mathematical thinking. It will explore real and abstract applications with and without the use of technology. The aims of this course are to develop students’ abilities in communication, critical thinking, generalization, problem-solving, etc. There are 6 content sections, as listed below. Of them, sections 3 and 5 are the key sections. 1. Numbers and algebra; 2. Functions; 3. Trigonometry and geometry; 4. Statistics and probability; 5. Calculus; 6. “Toolkit” and IA. Students will take IB Mathematics: Analysis and Approaches SL Exam after the course.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "pre": [["MAT011E71AA"]] }
                }, { "id": "MAT012E73AA",
