        }, "music": {
            "9": [
                {   "id": "MUS109E100",
                    "name": "Music and Performing Arts Culture and Administration 9 Standard",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "S",
                    "description": "In this course, students will learn the music industry skills, concepts, and methodologies necessary to manage the artistic, and ethical issues that face the contemporary music industry professional. Two available tracks within the course: pop music creation and art management. Pop music creation focuses in the history of pop music development which involves blues, jazz, rock, country to contemporary mainland pop music. After studying the history students will try to produce at least one piece using garage band software. Art management focuses in the case study covering theatre management, orchestra operation, festival operation, pop groups company at home and aboard. Students will learn basic management principles, methodologies from music perspective and practise in the real situation school activities such as arts festival, theatre festival, clubs. After one year of study, students should have the ability to: Understand and utilize key concepts of musical elements, including melody, rhythm, harmony, timbre, texture, form, etc. Understand important styles and works in the history of Western Art Music. Express themselves effectively with concise musical terminologies. Sing more effectively. Develop score analysis competency. Develop improvisation skills. Read, sight-sing, notate, and compose using the traditional notation system. Compose applying contemporary technologies, including but not limited to programming, mixing, recording, and AI technology. Additionally, though not treated as individual units, music from popular culture and folk traditions around the world will be introduced to enhance understanding of musical concepts.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future."
                }
            ], "10": [
                {   "id": "MUS110E130",
                    "name": "Music Appreciation 10 Honors",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "H",
                    "description": "This one-year course is designed as preparation for the IB/AP music program in 11th and 12th grades. Students will be taught within the framework of Western Art Music History, spanning from Ancient Greek to the 20th Century. Though the course is structured around classical music history, the real focus is to understand and apply musical concepts, including notation, melody, harmony, texture, timbre, form, etc., which have evolved over time. For each major period, at least one key musical concept will be covered. Students will gain experience in theoretical music theory, score analysis, contextual analysis, etc. Sight-singing: A short piece of melody will be offered to each student. With some practice time, the student is required to sing on the spot to a recording device.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": {
                        "current": [["MISSING: ENG 10S+"]], 
                        "next": [["MUS110E170"]]
                    }
                }, { "id": "MUS110E170",
                    "name": "AP Music Theory 10",
                    "track": "AP",
                    "description": "The AP Music Theory course is an advanced course equivalent to first-year college music theory. It aims to serve students who are interested in studying or pursuing music performance, composition, or musicology at university or conservatory. The course is an introduction to tonal harmony from the Common Practice Period (1600-1900) of music history. The course is designed to connect theoretical music concepts with recognition and practical application skills in order to cultivate a competent musician. The AP Course intends to enhance students' knowledge of the aesthetic design that is crucial for understanding the music of the past and changes in theory that led to the developments of 20th century music. Students will learn the systems used to analyze music at the micro and macro levels. In addition to studying musical scores, students will be expected to compose music and recreate common idioms as well as interpret music aurally(by year). Upon completion of this course, students will have developed a set of practical musical skills as well as a more intuitive musical ear.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": {
                        "pre": [["MUS110E130"]], 
                        "current": [["MISSING: ENG 10S+"]]
                    }
                }, { "id": "MUS110E131",
                    "name": "Western Theatre 10 Standard",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "S",
                    "description": "Aimed at providing students who intend to select the International Baccalaureate program (IB) Theatre Program in Grade 11 with a deeper understanding of this pre-college-level course and ensuring that they are adequately prepared, this year-long survey course in western theatre will cover the developments of and innovations in dramatic storytelling beginning with Sophocles’ tragedy Oedipus Rex in 429 BCE through the post-modern plays of Samuel Beckett in the twentieth century. As a result of their participation in this advanced theatre course, students will learn the relevant historical context of each major work, innovations in form, stagecraft, use of spectacle and audience expectations from each era, critical frameworks of analyses that will enhance the depth of their investigations into dramatic texts and a myriad of new plays, playwrights and dramatic styles that they may apply in their future academic careers as burgeoning theatre artists.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": { "next": [["MUS111E141"]] }
                }
            ], "11": [
                {   "id": "MUS111E100",
                    "name": "A Cappella & Ensemble Singing 11 Standard",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "S",
                    "description": "The 11th grade A Cappella & Ensemble Singing class is open to students who already have basic skills of singing or the ones who had taken the 9-10th grade A Cappella & Ensemble course before. The musical works students study in this course will be harder compared to the ones they have studied during 9-10th grade. This course will cover a wide range of repertoire and musical genres. Repertoire genres will include pop, movie music, art songs (classical), and musical theater; and will incorporate choreography. Other than that, students will also learn to rearrange A Cappella works. During school events, the group may possibly perform as a means to demonstrate the students’ progress, in addition to providing entertainment. Students will learn to cooperate as a group and work towards a shared goal. Performances and competitions inside and outside of school events will be an excellent chance to demonstrate school spirit. This class intends to achieve the following goals: 1) Singing skills: harder harmony training. 2) Ability to rearrange A Cappella works. 3) Singing Style: Show choir; a cappella; and other ensemble and genre types. 4) Opportunities for performances and competitions: Art Festival in school, performances inside and outside of school, and singing competitions outside school.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future."
                }, { "id": "MUS111E101",
                    "name": "Applied Acting Technique 11 Standard",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "S",
                    "description": "Using the textbook Theatre in Practice: A Student’s Handbook as our point of departure, students will learn the major theater practitioners of the past century (including Konstantine Stanislavski, Bertolt Brecht, Antonin Artuad, Jacques Lecoq and Steven Berkoff) as well as the important theater companies and artistic movements that have influenced acting techniques over the past several decades (including Cruel Theater, Complicite and Gecko) and apply these ideas to their own scripted and devised performances. At the end of the fall semester, students will be able to take one of the aforementioned practitioners/movements and apply these techniques to their own performance of a monologue or duologue that they selected from a list that the instructor provided; by the end of the spring semester, students will be expected to devise their own original play according to one of the prescribed models in the course content. As a result of their participation in this advanced acting course, students will receive requisite actor training necessary to excel at examinations for international theater curricula such as A-Level, IGCSE, Advanced Placement and International Baccalaureate, auditions and interviews for English-language theater programs in overseas universities, undergraduate acting classes and auditions for professional theater companies. By the end of this course, students will: 1) Possess a broad understanding of different and experimental frameworks of textual analysis and theater production, 2) Be trained in myriad different styles of acting technique that can be applied in many different circumstances, and 3) Have experience applying these skills to scripted, devised and improvised pieces.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future."
                }, { "id": "MUS111E102",
                    "name": "Opera and German - Austrian Art Song Singing 11 Standard",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "S",
                    "description": "Bel canto originated in Europe and is known as an elegant aristocratic singing method. It can mobilize all resonant cavities of the body, make the sound have super penetrating power and make you have brilliant and bright timbre. Opera is a western stage performance art and a comprehensive art form, based on Bel canto training, mainly or entirely in singing and music to explain and express the drama (is sung rather than spoken drama), It is called “the pearl on the crown of music and art”. Art song is an important vocal genre in the history of western music, based on Bel canto training. It is the perfect combination of poetry, voice, and music. Different countries have different names and styles of art songs. “Lied” in Germany, called “romance” in Russia and “melodie” in France. However, in terms of genre attributes, they all belong to the category of art songs, which are more delicate and perfect concert solo songs. which was created for specific poems, and the selected poems were highly literary. Deeply understanding and singing such works is conducive to cultivating students' artistic appreciation ability and singing ability. Aim: 1) Let students learn about the history of opera and art songs, as well as the representative composers of opera and art songs. 2) Let students master the pronunciation and poetry connotation of Italian, German and other lyrics. 3) Breath practice, so that each student can master the correct use of breath. 4) Use the five vowels \"a\", \"e\", \"i\", \"o\" ,\"u\" to practice students' chest resonance, oral resonance and head cavity resonance, so that each student has a bright voice, and has achieved the sound effect of overall resonance. 5) On the basis of understanding, sing opera excerpts and art songs.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future."
                }, { "id": "MUS111E140",
                    "name": "IB Music SL Y1",
                    "track": "IB",
                    "level": "SL",
                    "description": "The IB DP Music program is from Group 6 (The Arts) of the IB DP curriculum. It's a two-year program in which students will develop three major musical roles as Researchers, Creators, and Performers. The IB Music curriculum contains four major components, including Exploring Music in Context, Experimenting with Music, Presenting Music, and The Contemporary Music Maker. In the Exploring Music in Context component, students will be introduced to diverse musical material that will broaden their musical horizons and provide stimuli to expand their own music-making. In the Experimenting with Music component, students engage more deeply with chosen styles of music to develop and refine their musical decisions. In the Presenting Music component, students aim to polish and present their musical works in compositions, live performances, and program notes. The Contemporary Music Maker component is for HL candidates only. It culminates in a collaborative project inspired by real-life practices in contemporary music-making. Students will develop a holistic and in-depth understanding of music and develop competencies in solo and ensemble musical creation. In each component, students will engage in music-making roles as researchers, creators, and performers. They will submit musical works (compositions and performing recordings) and written reports as the outcome of each learned component.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": {
                        "pre": [["MUS110E130"]], 
                        "next": [["MUS112E140"]]
                    }
                }, { "id": "MUS111E150",
                    "name": "IB Music HL Y1",
                    "track": "IB",
                    "level": "HL",
                    "description": "The IB DP Music program is from Group 6 (The Arts) of the IB DP curriculum. It's a two-year program in which students will develop three major musical roles as Researchers, Creators, and Performers. The IB Music curriculum contains four major components, including Exploring Music in Context, Experimenting with Music, Presenting Music, and The Contemporary Music Maker. In the Exploring Music in Context component, students will be introduced to diverse musical material that will broaden their musical horizons and provide stimuli to expand their own music-making. In the Experimenting with Music component, students engage more deeply with chosen styles of music to develop and refine their musical decisions. In the Presenting Music component, students aim to polish and present their musical works in compositions, live performances, and program notes. The Contemporary Music Maker component is for HL candidates only. It culminates in a collaborative project inspired by real-life practices in contemporary music-making. Students will develop a holistic and in-depth understanding of music and develop competencies in solo and ensemble musical creation. In each component, students will engage in music-making roles as researchers, creators, and performers. They will submit musical works (compositions and performing recordings) and written reports as the outcome of each learned component.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": {
                        "pre": [["MUS110E130"]], 
                        "next": [["MUS112E150"]]
                    }
                }, { "id": "MUS111E141",
                    "name": "IB Theatre Y1",
                    "track": "IB",
                    "description": "This two-year course of study from the International Baccalaureate Organization combines the theoretical, literary and historical underpinnings of both western and eastern theatre-making with practical performance applications for students. Throughout their two years in the program, students will engage with theatrical conventions and practices through examining plays in context, involving themselves in the creative process and finally presenting their work to a live audience. The curriculum is further divided into four distinct components: working with play texts, examining world theatre traditions, collaboratively creating original theatre and finally creating theatre based on theatre history (the lattermost applying to students in the Higher Level only). Through participating in the IB Theatre Program, students will become effective theater artists and practitioners equipped with the requisite knowledge base and experience for success at the university level and beyond. By the end of this two-year program, students will: 1)Apply their research into theatre history, theory and criticism to a live theatrical production, 2)Compare and draw distinctions between the different practices of varying world theatre traditions, 3)Develop performances according to the theoretical frameworks of multiple influential dramatic theorists and practitioners, 4)Collaboratively create an original work of theatre for a live audience, and finally 5)Demonstrate their learning through recorded performances as well as through their performance on their IBO examinations.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future.",
                    "rules": {
                        "pre": [["MUS110E131"]], 
                        "current": [["MISSING: ENG 10H"]], "next": [["MUS112E141"]]
                    }
                }
            ], "12": [
                {   "id": "MUS112E104",
                    "name": "Digital Music Design 12 Standard",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "S",
                    "description": "The course aims to provide senior students in the International Division with opportunities for in-depth learning in composition, orchestration, and music production. Through practical course content, students will delve into various aspects of digital music design, ranging from creating original compositions to mastering music production processes and refining orchestration skills. They will gain extensive experience and skills in music production throughout the course. By the end of this course, students will be able to: 1) Master core skills in music composition, orchestration, and production, 2) Understand and apply theories and practices in digital music design, 3) Develop their creativity and style in the field of music production.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future."
                }, { "id": "MUS112E102",
                    "name": "Dramaturgy & Dramatic Criticism 12 Standard",
                    "track": "school",
                    "level": "S",
                    "description": "Using Aristotle’s Poetics, Stuart Spencer’s The Playwright’s Guidebook and David Ball’s Backwards and Forwards: A Technical Manual for Reading Plays as our textual points of departure, this course will cover the fundamental theoretical frameworks of analyses as well as the philosophical, aesthetic, compositional and stagecraft tenets that underpin western dramaturgy. Through learning how to root each play (and its playwright) in the historicity of its particular era as well as exploring the historiography of how attitudes and conventions concerning theater have changed over time, students will learn how to examine critically dramatic texts, productions and practices not as a set of doctrines to be followed but rather as tools that came into being for specific reasons during certain periods of time. At the end of the fall semester, students will be asked to produce an at least five-page essay on a topic of their choice (but must still be relevant to the course content); at the end of the spring semester, students will be required to watch a performance of their choice and produce an at least five-page review of the piece as a theater critic. As a result of their participation in this course, students will be able to understand a play’s narrative mechanics and construction, conduct script analyses, analyze and comment on plays as works of literature, critically examine the aesthetic ideologies and perspectives a dramatic text contains and approach new works of theater as informed audience members and critics. Aim: By the end of this course, students will: 1) Possess the intellectual equipment to analyze a play thoroughly, 2) Understand how to locate a dramatic text within its historical, social, economic and cultural context, 3) Gain the skills to conduct research on the production history of a play and how to apply this information to a new production of the play (or an adaptation of the piece), and finally 4) Know how to critically evaluate the quality of a new theater production in an informed and concise manner.",
                    "crowdRating": 6.7,
                    "crowdReview": "ISA - Hack the system. Build the future."
